Q: What value passed to the promise-resolving function causes the promise to be rejected with a TypeError? A: <p>A promise can resolve to another promise, but not to itself.</p>
<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="true" data-console="true" data-babel="false" data-babel-preset-react="false" data-babel-preset-ts="false">
<div class="snippet-code snippet-currently-hidden">
<pre class="snippet-code-js lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>let myPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) =&gt; {
  setTimeout(() =&gt; resolve(myPromise), 0);
});


myPromise.then(function() {
  console.log("normal")

}).catch(function(ex) {

  // this error is TypeError
  console.log(ex.message)

  console.log(ex instanceof TypeError)


})</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</p>
<p>But wait, let's try to trick javascript into circular resolution loop with a promise that resolves to a promise that resolves to the first one.</p>
<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="true" data-console="true" data-babel="false" data-babel-preset-react="false" data-babel-preset-ts="false">
<div class="snippet-code snippet-currently-hidden">
<pre class="snippet-code-js lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>let myPromise1 = new Promise((resolve, reject) =&gt; {
  setTimeout(() =&gt; resolve(myPromise2), 0);
});

let myPromise2 = new Promise((resolve, reject) =&gt; {
  setTimeout(() =&gt; resolve(myPromise1), 0);
});


myPromise1.then(function() {
  console.log("normal")
}).catch(function(ex) {

  // this error is TypeError
  console.log(ex.message)

  console.log(ex instanceof TypeError)

})</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</p>
<p>A surprising result, I was expecting a TypeError. But it didn't come and both Promises are now pending, forever.</p>

Q: Expo Router not working in Nx monorepo – stuck on splash / welcome screen A: <p>The issue is that your app directory is inside <code>src/</code>, but Expo Router by default looks for it at the project root (same level as app.json).</p>
<p>you should update your <code>app.json</code> to specify the correct root directory.</p>
<pre><code>{
  &quot;expo&quot;: {
    &quot;plugins&quot;: [
      [
        &quot;expo-router&quot;,
        {
          &quot;root&quot;: &quot;./src/app&quot;
        }
      ]
    ],
    &quot;scheme&quot;: &quot;your-app-scheme&quot;
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Or in your <code>metro.config.js</code>, configure the project root for the monorepo:</p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>const { getDefaultConfig } = require('expo/metro-config');
const { withNxMetro } = require('@nx/expo');
const path = require('path');

const config = getDefaultConfig(__dirname);

// Set the app directory for expo-router
process.env.EXPO_ROUTER_APP_ROOT = '../../apps/mobile/src/app';

module.exports = withNxMetro(config, {
  // Nx workspace root
  projectRoot: __dirname,
  workspaceRoot: path.resolve(__dirname, '../..'),
});
</code></pre>

Q: Xcode Preview crash with ModelContainer initialization A: <p><code>Preview</code> needs to be provided data just like you would at &quot;App&quot; level when you start the app on Simulator or on Device.</p>
<p>The best way to provide mock data for preview is using <code>PreviewModifier</code></p>
<p>Here is a sample SwiftData Modifier</p>
<pre><code>struct SwiftDataPreview: PreviewModifier {
    //All the Model types
    static let types: [any PersistentModel.Type] = [Item.self]

    //Make mock/sample context
    static func makeSharedContext() async throws -&gt; Context {
        let schema = Schema(types)
        //In Memory Context
        let config = ModelConfiguration(isStoredInMemoryOnly: true)
        let contailer = try ModelContainer(for: schema, configurations: config)
        let context = ModelContext(contailer)

        //Make any samples

        for n in (0...10) {
            let item = Item(timestamp: .now + TimeInterval(n))
            context.insert(item)
        }
        return context
    }

    typealias Context = ModelContext


    func body(content: Content, context: Context) -&gt; some View {
        content
            .modelContext(context)
    }
}
//Helper so you can access with dot notation
extension PreviewTrait where T == Preview.ViewTraits {
    @MainActor static var swiftDataInMemory: Self = .modifier(SwiftDataPreview())
}
</code></pre>
<p>Then you can use it with</p>
<pre><code>#Preview(traits: .swiftDataInMemory) {
    ContentView()
}

</code></pre>
